Ringgit Snaps Six-Day Rally as Euro Debt Crisis Damps Appetite

-- B y   D a v i d   Y o n g
-- 
2011-03-24T08:51:34Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-24/ringgit-snaps-six-day-rally-as-euro-debt-crisis-damps-appetite.html
Malaysia ’s ringgit fell for the
first time in seven days as concern  Europe ’s debt crisis will
worsen cooled demand for riskier assets, making it harder for
emerging markets to attract funds.  The currency retreated from near a 13-year high after
Portugal’s lawmakers rejected a plan to cut the nation’s budget
deficit, pushing the country closer to joining Greece and
Ireland in seeking an international bailout. Malaysia’s central
bank said yesterday inflation may double this year because of
higher commodity prices, damping the outlook for bonds ahead of
an auction next week.  “The market is focusing back on the Europe situation and
there’s some light follow-through selling,” said Azmi Shukri Rahman, a foreign-exchange trader at CIMB Investment Bank Bhd.
in  Kuala Lumpur . “The central bank is still hawkish and people
still want to buy the ringgit as it gets cheaper.”  The ringgit dropped 0.1 percent to 3.0285 per dollar as of
4:45 p.m. in Kuala Lumpur, according to data compiled by
Bloomberg. It touched 3.0240 on Feb. 21, the strongest level
since October 1997.  Bank Negara Malaysia  forecast consumer prices will rise by
2.5 percent to 3.5 percent this year, compared with a 1.7
percent gain in 2010. Crude  oil prices  have risen 15 percent
this year as political unrest in North Africa and the Middle
East has disrupted fuel supplies.  Consumer prices probably rose 2.7 percent in February from
a year earlier, the most since April 2009, according to the
median forecast in a Bloomberg News survey before a government
report tomorrow. They increased 2.4 percent in January.  The  finance ministry  will sell 4 billion ringgit ($1.3
billion) of bonds maturing in September 2014 on March 30,
according to data published by the central bank on its website.
The sale will take the tally this quarter to 24.5 billion
ringgit, a 29 percent increase over the same period last year.  The yield on the 3.434 percent note maturing in August 2014
climbed four basis points, or 0.04 percentage points, to 3.43
percent, according to Bursa Malaysia. The price dropped 0.15, or
1.5 ringgit per 1,000 ringgit face amount, to 100.  To contact the reporter on this story:
